message.content:
1. Intent-to-treat analyses were conducted on therapy attendance.
2. The therapy consisted of 16 sessions.
3. The therapy sessions were held weekly.
4. Patients were assigned to either the text messaging adjunct or the control condition.
5. Patients in the text messaging adjunct stayed in therapy significantly longer.
6. The median duration of therapy for patients in the text messaging adjunct was 13.5 weeks before dropping out.
7. The median duration of therapy for patients in the control condition was 3 weeks before dropping out.
8. The Wilcoxon-Mann-Whitney z score was -2.21.
9. The P value was .03.
10. The difference in therapy duration between the two groups was statistically significant.

messages.content:
Statement: Intent-to-treat analyses on therapy attendance during 16 sessions of weekly therapy found that patients assigned to the text messaging adjunct stayed in therapy significantly longer (median of 13.5 weeks before dropping out) than patients assigned to the control condition (median of 3 weeks before dropping out; Wilcoxon-Mann-Whitney z=−2.21, P=.03).
